ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, we fabricated a new kind of N, S- co-doped CDs for the rapid detection of toxic mercury(II) cations and two kinds of anions, cyanide and hydrosulfide based on their FL “on-off-on” and color changing behavior. Rubeanic acid (RA), one of the precursor, is widely used as a N, S-contained organic ligand for transition metal ions [33–35]. We expect that RA would show superior properties for doping CDs with nitrogen and sulfur, largely because it has a higher molar ratio of nitrogen and sulfur to carbon (C:N:S = 1:1:1) than that of usual N, S- co-doping material, namely sulfhydryl amino acid (mostly l-cysteine) (C:N:S = 3:1:1). The previously reported N, S-doped carbon dots generally use –SH as sulfur source [30–32,36]. In this study, we suggest that CS group involved RA may be more workable than –SH for the functionalization of N, S- co-doped carbon dots. Specifically, NSCDs are synthesized by using citric acid (CA) and RA as precursors through a facile one step microwave-assisted hydrothermal method. The fluorescent quantum yield (FLQY) of NSCDs after dialysis is determined as 17.6%, which is higher than most existed N, S-CDs (see Table 1
                     ). Moreover, the as-synthesized NSCDs exhibit splendid sensing applications. Upon the addition of Hg2+ in aqueous solution, the fluorescence of NSCDs can be dramatically quenched due to the formation of coordination complexes. Furthermore, adding cyanide or hydrosulfide anions to NSCDs@Hg2+ complexes (CD-Hg) results in a considerable fluorescence recovery or a notable color change (Scheme 1
                     ), respectively. By spectral investigation at different pH values, the practicable working capability of NSCDs versus pH has been determined as 6–8, which suggests their potential applications in bio-image and sensing.
